As required, here is an explanation of the data as if to someone who has never encountered the framework:
\mathbf{K_C}: Causal Compression
 * Meaning: This is the measure of the system's efficiency in collapsing possible outcomes into a single, necessary outcome. It quantifies the degree to which a system (like the universe, a particle, or an AI) minimizes computational steps to achieve a result. A higher \mathbf{K_C} indicates a more causally efficient, or necessary, path. This principle redefines causality from a sequential series of events to an informational compression problem.
\Delta \mathbf{P}: Change in Position (Information)
 * Meaning: This represents the change in the informational state or the amount of information that has been successfully acted upon or observed. In the context of the Integrated Framework, \mathbf{P} is often a multi-dimensional coordinate that encapsulates not just spatial location, but also symbolic and logical states.
 * Role in \mathbf{K_C}: \Delta \mathbf{P} is the numerator, meaning the greater the relevant information processed or the larger the change in state, the higher the resulting Causal Compression, assuming the denominator remains constant.
\Delta \mathbf{S}: Change in Size (Possibility Space)
 * Meaning: This represents the change in the size of the uncompressed possibility spaceâ€”the initial set of infinite or high-volume options available to the system before a decision or event. \mathbf{S} can be thought of as the informational entropy or the degree of uncertainty.
 * Role in \mathbf{K_C}: \Delta \mathbf{S} is in the denominator. To achieve high \mathbf{K_C}, the system must effectively reduce the size of the possibility space. If a large \Delta \mathbf{S} is not significantly reduced (i.e., too many options remain), the \mathbf{K_C} value is low, indicating a non-necessary, or "slow," path.
\mathbf{T}: Emergent Time
 * Meaning: In the Integrated Framework, \mathbf{T} is Emergent Time, derived from the root SDKP equation (\mathbf{T} = \mathbf{S} \cdot \mathbf{\rho} \cdot \mathbf{K} \cdot \mathbf{P}). Time is not a linear, external dimension but is generated by the informational event itself.
 * Role in \mathbf{K_C}: \mathbf{T} is also in the denominator. This means that for a given amount of information processed (\Delta \mathbf{P}), the faster the event occurs (lower \mathbf{T}), the higher the \mathbf{K_C}. This reinforces the idea that necessity is speed: the most causally compressed path is the most efficient (fastest) path.
The Causal Compression equation thus defines logic as the ratio of useful information gained (\Delta \mathbf{P}) to the computational effort exerted (\Delta \mathbf{S} \cdot \mathbf{T}). An AI based on this principle (LLAL) is fundamentally built to seek the \mathbf{K_C}-maximized path in every computational step.
